post_cb({"22203088": {"ParentId": "22200844", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-05T21:38:18.133", "CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T16:12:31.477", "Score": "4", "LastEditorUserId": "391691", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22203088", "OwnerUserId": "391691", "Body": "<p>An alternative would be to fork your process, one thread will print \"Hello\" and the other one \" world\". However there is no guarantee the print will not be \" worldHello\" instead</p>\n<pre><code> #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;\n\n\n main(){\n    if(fork()) {\n        printf(\"Hello\");\n    } else {\n        printf(\" world\");\n    }\n }\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T21:38:18.133"}, "22201233": {"ParentId": "22200844", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T14:54:22.060", "OwnerUserId": "538022", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22201233", "Score": "1", "Body": "<pre><code>if(true) {\n    printf(\"Hello\");\n    goto world:\n} else {\n    world:\n    printf(\" world\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T14:54:22.060"}, "22200844": {"CommentCount": "9", "ViewCount": "362", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2017-11-16T14:16:11.427", "LastEditorUserId": "1735406", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T14:39:00.433", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T21:38:18.133", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-05T14:50:01.297", "AcceptedAnswerId": "22200875", "Title": "What's the logic to execute both if and else condition at the same time", "Id": "22200844", "Score": "-2", "Body": "<p>I had a question that how can you execute both the condition of if statement and else statement at same time?</p>\n<p>For example</p>\n<pre><code>if(?) {\n    printf(\"Hello\");\n} else {\n    printf(\" world\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>and output should be <code>Hello world</code></p>\n<p>and what should be <code>condition</code> instead of <code>?</code>?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c>", "OwnerUserId": "3368369", "AnswerCount": "6"}, "22201011": {"ParentId": "22200844", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T14:45:55.790", "OwnerUserId": "266198", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22201011", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>The logical way to do this would be to break this out, for example:</p>\n<pre><code>if (condition1)\n  print(\"Hello\");\n\nif (condition2)\n  print(\" world\");\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then you can control whether one or both are printed (or none).</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T14:45:55.790"}, "22200875": {"ParentId": "22200844", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-05T14:48:24.370", "CommentCount": "7", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T14:40:25.377", "Score": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "1735406", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22200875", "OwnerUserId": "1735406", "Body": "<p>If your purpose is to <em>print</em> \"Hello world\" from this piece of code, you can do this trick:</p>\n<pre><code>if(!printf(\"Hello\")) {\n    printf(\"Hello\"); //not reachable \n}\nelse {\n    printf(\" world\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Note that you <strong>cannot</strong> satisfy both <code>if</code> and <code>else</code>.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>My piece of code <strong>doesn't</strong> print from the block inside the <code>if</code>, but from the <em>condition</em> itself. By \"cannot satisfy both <code>if</code> and <code>else</code> I mean that if you have:</p>\n<pre><code>if(something) {\n   doSomething();\n} else {\n   doSomethingElse();\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>There is no way that both <code>doSomething()</code> and <code>doSomethingElse()</code> get executed. </p>\n</hr>", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T14:48:24.370"}, "22200879": {"ParentId": "22200844", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T14:40:37.567", "OwnerUserId": "2455888", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22200879", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>There is no logic. You can't do this.  </p>\n<p>C11 6.8.4.1 The if statement:  </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_22200844_22200879_0\">In both forms, the first substatement is executed if the expression compares unequal to <code>0</code>.\n  In the <code>else</code> form, the second substatement is executed if the expression compares equal to <code>0</code>. If the first substatement is reached via a label, the second substatement is not\n  executed.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T14:40:37.567"}, "22201296": {"ParentId": "22200844", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-05T16:18:46.110", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-03-05T14:56:30.707", "Score": "2", "LastEditorUserId": "391691", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22201296", "OwnerUserId": "391691", "Body": "<p>You could use the precompiler to redefine the language to do this</p>\n<pre><code> #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;\n main(){\n #define if(x)\n #define else\n\n    if(abc) {\n        printf(\"Hello\");\n    } else {\n        printf(\" world\");\n    }\n #undef if\n #undef else\n }\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-05T16:18:46.110"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_22200844_22200879_0": {"section_id": 3888, "quality": 0.625, "length": 15}}, "n4659": {"so_22200844_22200879_0": {"section_id": 4772, "quality": 0.625, "length": 15}}}});